Machine Learning: Logistic Regression

2017-06-11

1 Logistic Regression

Logistic Regression is a regression model in which the response variable is categorical. Instead of trying to predict the numerical value of an outcome variable, well predict the probability that the outcome is in one of two classes. Since this probability will vary between 0 and 1 we need to have a function which saturates at these extremes. There are a variety of functions which will do this for us, but well use the logistic function \[ P(Y = 1 | X) = \frac{e^{\beta_0 + \beta_1 X}}{1 + e^{\beta_0 + \beta_1 X}}. \] Using a bit of algebra this can be transformed into \[ \frac{P(Y = 1 | X)}{1 - P(Y = 1 | X)} = e^{\beta_0 + \beta_1 X}. \] The quantity on the left is known as the odds. One more step gives us the log odds or logit \[ \log\left(\frac{P(Y = 1 | X)}{1 - P(Y = 1 | X)}\right) = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X. \] The logit function is known as the link function. An alternative link function is the probit function.

In R a Logistic Regression model is created using glm() which builds a Generalized Linear Models. This function actually caters for a wide range of models, but we select a logistic model by specifying that the residuals have a Binomial distribution via the family parameter.

The plots above illustrate the effect of varying \(\beta_0\) and \(\beta_1\):

  1. \(\beta_0 = 0\) and \(\beta_1 = 1\) (sigmoid centred on \(x = 0\));
  2. \(\beta_0 > 0\) (shifts sigmoid left);
  3. \(\beta_0 < 0\) (shifts sigmoid right);
  4. \(\beta_1 < 1\) (more gradual transition); and
  5. \(\beta_1 > 1\) (more rapid transition).

1.2 Principle of Parsimony

Everything should be made as simple as possible, but not simpler.Albert Einstein

The Principle of Parsimony is that we should try to make our models as simple as possible (but no simpler!). Therefore all features which dont appear to have any predictive value should be excluded from the model and it should be trimmed down to the bare essentials. Only include those terms which have a significant effect on the outcome.

Its obvious that we could build a more parsimonious model above by simply neglecting the terms for x and y. However, lets have a look at an automated way of refining the model. Well use Stepwise Regression to systematically consider various combinations of predictor variables and arrive at the one which produces the best model.

The stepAIC() function from the MASS package considers stepwise changes in the model formula, at each stage selecting the change which results in the lowest AIC.

library(MASS)
redblue.glm <- stepAIC(redblue.glm, direction = "both")
Start:  AIC=96.82
colour ~ x + y + r

       Df Deviance     AIC
- y     1   89.984  95.984
<none>      88.816  96.816
- x     1   91.624  97.624
- r     1  309.589 315.589

Step:  AIC=95.98
colour ~ x + r

       Df Deviance     AIC
<none>      89.984  95.984
- x     1   92.791  96.791
+ y     1   88.816  96.816
- r     1  309.837 313.837

There are three stages in the stepwise regression procedure above:

  1. Consider the model colour ~ x + y + r and gauge the effect of removing the terms x, y and r. Removing either x or y results in an improved AIC.
  2. Consider the model colour ~ y + r and gauge the effect of removing the terms y and r, or adding the term x. Only removing y results in an improved AIC.
  3. Consider the model colour ~ r and gauge the effect of removing the term r, or adding the terms x and y. None of these result in an improved model.

The final model is thus based on colour ~ r.

1.3 Multicollinearity

Sometimes variables within a dataset can be highly correlated with each other. Severe multicollinearity is a problem because it can increase the variance of the coefficient estimates and make the estimates very sensitive to minor changes in the model. Consider the following example:

Suppose that you are trying to model probability of being married and use both years and weeks since birth as predictors. Since years and weeks are highly correlated, the estimates in the model will be ambiguous. So, it may say that 50% of marriage rate is achieved when you are 26 years and 0 weeks old, or 0 years 1 357 weeks old, or maybe 15 years and 574 weeks. You see that the estimates of the years/weeks are not exact because one can flow into the other and back (and thats the definition of strong multicollinearity). In the regression model output it will show up as a large error of the estimate for the coefficients. Obviously, in this case, you can convert years to weeks and vice versa. But when you dont clearly know the objective relationship between two variables, its impossible to interpret the individual variables on the basis of of their coefficients.

The presence of multicollinearity isnt the end of the world and can be addressed by getting more data, removing one variable, or employing different regression techniques like Decision Trees or Ridge Regression.

2 Model Evaluation

Its all very well constructing a model performs well on the training data. But the true test is performance on unseen or holdout data. Luckily we have been disciplined and retained a separate, untouch stash of data that we can use for testing. Now we have a number of options for precisely how we formulate those tests.

2.1 Confusion Matrix

The first and simplest method for assessing a classification model is a Confusion Matrix, which tabulates the count of predicted outcomes against known outcomes for the test data.

Observed
Negative Positive
Predicted Negative True Negative (TN) False Negative (FN)
Positive False Positive (FP) True Positive (TP)

The four cells in a confusion matrix have counts for the number of true positives, false positives, false negatives and true negatives. The confusionMatrix() function in the caret package can be used to easily generate a confusion matrix. Its important to ensure that this function correctly identifies the positive class in your model (if not then it can be specified by the positive argument).

(confuse <- confusionMatrix(predict(myopia.glm, myopia.test), myopia.test$myopic, positive = "Yes"))

2.2 Accuracy

Accuracy is simply the fraction of cases which are correctly predicted. Its defined as

\[ \text{accuracy} = (TP + TN) / (TP + FN + TN + FP). \]

Unfortunately accuracy is a pretty poor indicator of model performance, especially in the case of imbalanced data.

The No Information Rate is simply the proportion of the most common class in the data. This is the probability that you would be right in just guessing the most common class. The model accuracy can be compared to the no information rate and the resulting p-value indicates whether or not one can reject the null hypothesis that the model is no better than guessing the most common class.

2.3 Sensitivity

Sensitivity, also known as Recall or True Positive Rate (TPR), is an indication of what proportion of data which are observed to be in the positive class are labelled correctly. Sensitivity is also known as the True Positive Rate (TPR). The larger the sensitivity the fewer true positives will be missed by the model.

\[ \text{sensitivity} = TP / (TP + FN) \]

A model with high sensitivity is likely to result in many Type I errors but few Type II errors (think of an extremely sensitive metal detector).

2.4 Precision

Precision indicates what fraction of the data which are labelled positive were actually observed to be positive.

\[ \text{precision} = TP / (TP + FP) \]

2.5 Specificity

Specificity, also known as True Negative Rate" (TNR), quantifies the models ability to correctly identify negative outcomes. Its the probability of a negative prediction given that the observed outcome is negative.

\[ \text{specificity} = TN / (TN + FP) = 1 - FPR.\]

The inverse of specificity is the False Positive Rate (FPR). The FPR is the proportion of negative cases that incorrectly labelled as positive.

In a medical setting the specificity would be the proportion of healthy patients who test negative for a disease.

A model with high specificity is likely to result in many Type II errors but few Type I errors (think of an extremely rigorous job selection process: many potentially good candidates will be rejected and only a few will be selected).

Sensitivity and specificity. Image courtesy of Wikipedia.

2.6 Positive/Negative Predictive Value

The Positive Predictive Value (PPV) is the probability that the outcome is really positive given a positive prediction. The Negative Predictive Value (NPV) is the probability that the outcome is really negative given a negative prediction.

It should be apparent that PPV is the same as Precision.

2.7 F Measure

The \(F\) measure is a weighted combination of other error metrics.

\[ F_\beta = (1 + \beta^2) \frac{\text{sensitivity} \cdot \text{precision}}{\text{sensitivity} + \beta^2 \cdot \text{precision}}. \]

The relative importance of the constituent metrics is determined by the \(\beta\) coefficient. \(\beta\) is often set to 1, in which case one refers to the \(F_1\) measure, which is simply the harmonic mean of sensitivity and precision.

\[ F_1 = 2 \frac{\text{sensitivity} \cdot \text{precision}}{\text{sensitivity} + \text{precision}}. \]

\(F_1\) varies from 0 to 1, where 1 is a perfect classifier (complete sensitivity and precision).

2.8 ROC and AUC

The Receiver Operating Characteristics (ROC) curve is one of the most popular ways of assessing model performance. The ROC curve reflects the change in True Positive Rate (TPR) versus False Positive Rate (FPR) as the classification threshold is varied.

library(ROCR)

myopia.prediction <- prediction(predict(myopia.glm, newdata = myopia.test, type = "prob")[, "Yes"],
                                myopia.test$myopic)
#
# Note that prediction() requires probabilities rather than the predicted classes.
#
plot(performance(myopia.prediction, measure = "tpr", x.measure = "fpr"))
abline(a = 0, b = 1)

The threshold is 1 in the bottom left of the plot and decreases towards 0 in the top right. Varying the threshold results in different levels of sensitivity and specificity. When the threshold is close to 1 the classifier is conservative, only labelling a case as positive if the probability is high. As a result there are fewer false positives (but it will also miss many positive cases, reducing the number of true positives). A threshold closer to zero will result in more positive predictions, which in turns produces more true positives (but at the same time also more false positives!).

As is evident from the ROC curve above, unless you have a perfect classifier, there will always be a tradeoff between TPR and FPR. By varying the value of the threshold you can tune your model either maximise the TPR or minimise the FPR.

performance(myopia.prediction, measure = "auc")@y.values
[[1]]
[1] 0.9275701

AUC varies between 0 and 1, although values below 0.5 should not be achieved in practice. An AUC of 0.5 would be the same as a random guess; values greater than 0.8 indicate a good classifier, while those exceeding 0.9 are excellent.

3 Costs of Errors

Consider a model for automated security screening at an airport. The positive class corresponds to a passenger who is carrying a bomb. The occurrence of the positive class is relatively infrequent.

Is it more important to minimise false positives or false negatives?

True positive and true negative results have no cost. A false positive has little cost (the passenger in question would just be manually screened and the error would be rectified). A false negative, on the other hand, would have a massive cost because the threat would not have been detected.

The total cost is

\[ C(TP) \cdot TP + C(TN) \cdot TN + C(FP) \cdot FP + C(FN) \cdot FN \]

where

  • \(C(TP)\) is the cost of a true positive (generally this is zero);
  • \(C(TN)\) is the cost of a true negative (generally this is zero);
  • \(C(FP)\) is the cost of a false positive;
  • \(C(FN)\) is the cost of a false negative.

  3. Use the birthwt data in the MASS package to construct a model for low birth weight. Are there any features which should be excluded from the model?

The four predictors are the percentages of four ingredients: tricalcium aluminate (x1), tricalcium silicate (x2), tetracalcium alumino ferrite (x3), and dicalcium silicate (x4). Make a linear regression with all predictors and find their variance inflation factors. Is there anything troubling? What would severe multicollinearity mean for interpreting the variables?
